This is defined in terms of `Finset.HasAntidiagonal`.

A subsequent PR #9309 uses this to compute coefficients of products of power series.

Co-author : Maria Ines de Frutos Fernandez

Based on work of Bhavik Mehta in `Archive/Partition.lean`

nodes.body:
The `Fin.hasPiAntidiagonal_univ` instance will probably be good enough to replace docs#Finset.Nat.antidiagonalTuple but there's an issue of what the right definition of `HasPiAntidiagonal` should be. 
For applications (such as ours, or `cut` in Partition.lean), I think we need not only functions from a fintype, but functions from an arbitrary type, except that we bound the support. 
Playing with coercions (from the fintype associated with the finset, to the ambient type) will probably be tedious.

:v: AntoineChambert-Loir can now approve this pull request. To approve and merge a pull request, simply reply with `bors r+`. More detailed instructions are available [here](https://bors.tech/documentation/getting-started/#reviewing-pull-requests).

Thanks @eric-wieser  for the modifications you made. It is cool that everything is now computable.

I was aware of one issue (for piAntidiagonal) but didn't know how to start the proof; I don't know whether the sequence `(Fintype.truncEquivFinOfCardEq <| Fintype.card_coe s).lift` deserves to be extracted from that code, but at least it needs to be exemplified somewhere in tutorials.

The other computability issues you solved probably deserve to be extracted to mathlib, don't you think?

My impression is that this refactor would be moot without applications like the one for power series. Then, how can one be sure that a PR will lead to such applications if they are not included in it? Chaining pull requests?

This refactor is sufficiently justified by the fact it cleans up something in the archive; but indeed, dependent PRs are the preferred way to demonstrate how a more basic result will later be used in something more complicated.

My claim is that you can write
```
def piAntidiagonal [HasAntidiagonal α] (s : Finset ι) (a : α) : Finset (ι →₀ α)
```
and that the only reasonable implementation has the same complexity as any α-specific implementation.

The analogy here is that we have no `FiniteSum` typeclass; we derive `Finset.sum` from `Add`

I assume `Finsupp.cons` is what makes this `noncomputable`? I think for this function it would be best to stay computable and return
```suggestion
def finAntidiagonal : (d : ℕ) → μ → Finset (Fin d → μ)
```
Since it's easy to convert to finsupp later.
Done. For the moment I've kept a Finsupp variant (with an index 0)

I think the notation is a little nicer here:

Uh, I doubt we want this? Either you replace `Finset.map` everywhere or you simply use `Finset.image` in your application.

Note that `Finset.preimage` will soon change from assuming `s.InjOn f` to `s.FinitelyFiberedOn f`.

This comes from https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Finset.2EInjOn.2Emap/near/404409525
but I hadn't adjusted the name.
```
def _root_.Finset.InjOn.map {α β : Type*} {f : α → β}
    (s : Finset α) (hs : Set.InjOn f s) : Finset β  :=
  s.attach.map { inj' := hs.injective }
```
In any case, subsequent modifications made it useless here, so I just deleted it.
This doesn't belong in `BigOperators`; can you put it in `Finsupp.Basic` instead?
OK. It is at a slightly bizarre place because, making use of your next comment, it has to be included after docs#Finsupp.comapDomain
This is `Finsupp.comapDomain`, I think
yes. I use that, thanks!
Is there a lemma you can use here about `embDomain _ (comapDomain _ _)`? If not, can you write that lemma?

The only existing way would rewrite `embDomain` as `mapDomain`, but this assumes `AddCommMonoid M`, which is not needed.
I'll write that lemma.

(mapDomain sums over preimages, but when f is injective, the sum is reduced to a subsingleton).
On the other hand, docs#mapDomain_comapDomain makes an injectivity assumption; my guess is that it should be rephrased as  embDomain_comapDomain, and the initial mapDomain_comapDomain proved in terms of it.
